  "articleSummary": "The article analyzes why Google's self-driving cars are involved in twice as many accidents as human drivers, arguing that the crashes are primarily caused by human drivers unfamiliar with robotic behavior, not by AI failures. It explores the ethical and legal dilemmas (the trolley problem) of programming cars to obey traffic laws absolutely, which makes them overly cautious and prone to being rear-ended. The author proposes a three-tier system of flexible rule adherence to mimic human driving, balancing strict law-following with situational awareness. The tone is analytical and advocacy-oriented, aimed at tech enthusiasts and policymakers, using the metaphor of robots driving like \"octogenarians\" to critique their rigidity.",
